About
The Ocean√°rio de Lisboa is a world-renowned public aquarium, an inspiring ‚Äúwindow‚Äù into the ocean, establishing an emotional connection with the public, and encouraging positive personal relationships with the ocean. Ocean√°rio de Lisboa is one of the largest aquariums in Europe -featuring over 15,000 marine creatures from 500 species! - and one of the most visited places in Portugal, just 10 min. away from Lisbon airport. It has been recognize for three times as the "best aquarium in the world" by TripAdvisor's Travellers'Choice. Visitors can see, among others, Magellanic penguins, sea otters, rays and several species of sharks and corals. The ticket includes three exhibits - and it contributes to the conservation of the ocean and marine biodiversity. This attraction is a popular stop on hop-on hop-off bus tours in Lisbon, including audio guides in several languages. ‚Äì Tripadvisor

The area

Neighborhood: Parque das Na√ß√µes
This neighborhood was built up at the end of the 1990s mostly because of the Expo '98. The pavilions and structures that once were the home of all the Expo's attractions and exhibits are still culturally and artistically significant. In Parque das Na√ß√µes you'll explore conference and concert pavilions, a shopping center, trendy restaurants and an enjoyable cable car ride you can't miss out on. On top of this, the amazing Lisbon Oceanarium (one of the most spectacular things you'll ever see in the city) will take your breath away: its respect and will to preserve natural wildlife is uncanny. Easily accessible by metro, bus or taxi from the city center, Parque das Na√ß√µes is highly recommended for anyone who'll spend more than 3 days in the Portuguese capital.

Brittany_11_10
Los Angeles, CA1,856 contributions
Excellent, educational aquarium
Sep 2024 ‚Ä¢ Family
For us (two adults, two seniors, and a toddler), this aquarium lived up to the hype/all the positive things we'd read about it ahead of time.

It seemed like the main complaint was the crowds, and the main suggestion was to go at opening (or way late afternoon/early evening), but we went mid-afternoon, I think around 2pm, and only at the very end (you go in one direction, so there is a pretty clear start and end) did it get crowded--and then it was, indeed, QUITE crowded. But the rest of the time, viewing the main aquarium, the penguins, the otters, the tropical fish, everything on the upper level, we had no issues with feeling like it was too crowded at all.

The main aquarium is awesome. You can see it from two floors, and from so many different vantage points. There were a number of times where we were the only ones looking from a particular section. There was a good variety of marine life in it as well, and the animals looked healthy.

While I much prefer seeing marine life in the wild (snorkeling and/or scuba diving), this aquarium also did a great job of trying to educate visitors. Just about every placard I read seemed to talk about environmental issues affecting whatever species was being described, and sometimes possible ways to help combat the issues. Nicely done, in that regard. And there was a little station on the top level where you could ask staff members questions, and they had some items on display that you (or your excited toddler, in our case) could touch and talk about.

In addition to the main tank being a highlight, we also loved the otter exhibit. And it was fun to watch penguins dive in the water to catch their fish, and then eat it.

We definitely could have spent more time here, and I highly recommend it to anyone who likes aquariums and/or who wants to show their child/children marine life they can't yet see on their own in the wild, especially since they seemed very keen on educating and not just displaying.
